INSERT INTO `destination` VALUES (64,'Sigiriya','The iconic Lion Rock, a UNESCO-listed 5th-century CE fortress and palace complex rising 200m from the central plains. Famous for its ancient frescoes, water gardens, and panoramic views from the summit.',1,'Matale, Sri Lanka',7.95700000,80.76030000,'2026-02-10 14:13:08',1,'2026-02-10 14:13:08',NULL,NULL,NULL,35,'Sigriya lion rock and museum'),(65,'Kandy','Nestled in the lush central highlands, Kandy is the soul of Sri Lankan culture. This sacred city, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is home to the revered Temple of the Sacred Tooth Relic, one of Buddhism\'s holiest shrines',1,'Kandy, Sri Lanka',7.29362700,80.64135000,'2026-02-10 15:49:06',NULL,'2026-02-10 15:49:06',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(66,'Nuwara Eliya','Sri Lanka\'s premier hill country retreat, known as \"Little England\" for its colonial-era bungalows and Tudor-style buildings. Nestled at 1,889 meters elevation, this former British hill station boasts year-round spring-like temperatures (10-19°C), rolling tea plantations established by Scottish planter James Taylor in 1867, and a charming lake. Attractions include Horton Plains National Park with \"World\'s End\" cliff, Hakgala Botanical Garden, and Asia\'s oldest golf course (1889). The region produces world-famous Ceylon high-grown tea, with several working factories open to visitors',1,'Central Province, Sri Lanka',6.96940000,80.76970000,'2026-02-12 19:46:25',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(67,'Ella','A picturesque mountain village nestled in the central highlands at approximately 1,041 meters above sea level. Famous as the terminus of the world-renowned scenic train journey from Kandy, Ella captivates visitors with its dramatic landscapes—misty mountains carpeted in emerald tea plantations, lush forests, and cascading waterfalls. Key attractions include the iconic Nine Arch Bridge (a 91-meter colonial-era architectural marvel built without steel), the relatively easy trek to Little Adam\'s Peak for panoramic valley views, the more challenging Ella Rock hike (1,348m), and the powerful 25-meter Ravana Falls. The surrounding area is dotted with working tea factories offering tours ',1,'Badulla District, Uva Province, Sri Lanka',6.86740000,81.04230000,'2026-02-12 19:52:53',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(68,'Yala','Sri Lanka\'s most visited and second-largest national park (spanning 97,880 hectares), renowned for possessing the world\'s highest density of leopards. Nestled in the island\'s southeast corner, the park encompasses a spectacular variety of ecosystems—from monsoon forests and open plains to freshwater lakes and coastal lagoons. It shelters an abundance of wildlife including Asian elephants, sloth bears, wild buffalo, jackals, sambar deer, spotted deer, mugger crocodiles, and over 215 bird species (including several endemics). Ancient archaeological ruins, including 2nd-century BC stupas, lie hidden within the jungle. Block 1 (Ruhuna National Park), dating to 1900, is the most visited area',1,'Southern and Uva Provinces, Sri Lanka',6.37280000,81.51690000,'2026-02-12 19:54:57',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(69,'Benthota','A dreamy palm-fringed coastal resort town on Sri Lanka\'s southwestern shore, nestled between the Bentota River (Bentara Ganga) and the Indian Ocean. Famous for its golden sandy beaches and water sports, Bentota offers a perfect blend of relaxation and adventure. Highlights include serene river safaris through mangrove forests, visits to the Kosgoda Turtle Hatchery (conserving all five Sri Lankan turtle species), the stunning Lunuganga Estate (country home of renowned architect Geoffrey Bawa), and historic Buddhist temples like Galapatha Viharaya (dating to the 2nd century BC). The town sits at the mouth of the Bentota River, with the former Portuguese/Dutch fort area now housing a rest house with colonial history ',1,'Galle District, Southern Province, Sri Lanka',6.42000000,79.99690000,'2026-02-12 19:57:24',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(70,'Galle','A vibrant UNESCO World Heritage Site famous for the Galle Fort—the best-preserved European fortification in Asia, originally built by the Portuguese in 1587 and magnificently fortified by the Dutch from 1640 onwards. The fort is a living monument where colonial-era buildings (now housing chic cafes, boutiques, museums, and hotels) coexist harmoniously with courts, schools, and everyday commerce within massive ramparts and bastions. Visitors can stroll cobblestone streets past the Dutch Reformed Church (1755), the Galle Lighthouse (Sri Lanka\'s oldest), the National Maritime Museum (housed in a 1671 VOC warehouse), and enjoy a distinctively Mediterranean atmosphere. Beyond the fort, the region offers golden beaches, rainforest reserves (Kanneliya), and tea experiences',1,'Galle District, Southern Province, Sri Lanka',6.03190000,80.21750000,'2026-02-12 19:58:50',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(71,'Mirissa','A relaxed seaside town on Sri Lanka\'s southern coast, sitting between Weligama and Matara. While retaining a laid-back, budget-friendly vibe with backpacker accommodation and homestays, Mirissa has gained international fame as the premier whale watching hub—offering 90%+ sighting success rates for blue whales between November and April. The town features beautiful crescent-shaped beaches, the Instagram-famous Coconut Tree Hill (best visited at sunrise), Parrot Rock viewpoint (tide-dependent access), and a \"Secret Beach\" with two secluded coves. It also boasts the largest fishing port on the south coast, ensuring excellent fresh seafood. Accommodation ranges from simple guesthouses to the upcoming Ritz Carlton (projected 2027 opening) ',1,'Southern Province, Sri Lanka',5.94500000,80.45200000,'2026-02-12 19:59:09',NULL,'2026-02-13 18:14:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(72,'Anuradhapura','Ancient capital city with sacred temples and historical ruins',1,'Anuradhapura, Sri Lanka',8.31140000,80.40370000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(73,'Polonnaruwa','Historic city with ancient ruins and UNESCO heritage sites',1,'Polonnaruwa, Sri Lanka',7.94030000,81.01880000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(74,'Jaffna','Cultural city known for Tamil heritage, temples, and colonial history',1,'Jaffna, Sri Lanka',9.66150000,80.02550000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(75,'Colombo','Commercial capital with colonial buildings, temples, and urban attractions',1,'Colombo, Sri Lanka',6.92710000,79.86120000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(76,'Adams Peak','Famous pilgrimage mountain with scenic hiking trails',1,'Nallathanniya, Sri Lanka',6.80960000,80.49940000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(77,'Horton Plains','High altitude plateau with World’s End cliff and hiking trails',1,'Horton Plains, Sri Lanka',6.80670000,80.80730000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(78,'Haputale','Mountain town offering hiking trails and panoramic views',1,'Haputale, Sri Lanka',6.76500000,80.95100000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(79,'Arugam Bay','Popular surfing destination with beautiful beaches',1,'Arugam Bay, Sri Lanka',6.84040000,81.83680000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(80,'Batticaloa','Eastern coastal city with beaches and lagoons',1,'Batticaloa, Sri Lanka',7.71700000,81.70000000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(81,'Hikkaduwa','Famous beach with coral reefs and vibrant nightlife',1,'Hikkaduwa, Sri Lanka',6.14070000,80.10120000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(82,'Hiriketiya','Beautiful bay popular for surfing and relaxation',1,'Hiriketiya, Sri Lanka',5.96400000,80.70470000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(83,'Hambantota','Coastal city with beaches and wildlife attractions',1,'Hambantota, Sri Lanka',6.12410000,81.11850000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(84,'Gal Oya','National park famous for boat safaris and wildlife',1,'Gal Oya, Sri Lanka',7.22200000,81.48100000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(85,'Hatton','Hill country town surrounded by tea plantations and mountains',1,'Hatton, Sri Lanka',6.89160000,80.59550000,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,'2026-02-18 16:48:28',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(86,'Kalpitiya','A stunning peninsula on Sri Lanka\'s northwest coast, renowned as one of Asia\'s best kitesurfing destinations with consistent winds from May to October. The area is famous for dolphin and whale watching, with large pods of spinner dolphins visible just offshore. Home to the Bar Reef Marine Sanctuary, Sri Lanka\'s largest coral reef system with over 100 coral species and 300 tropical fish species. The 17th-century Dutch Fort stands as a reminder of colonial history, while miles of uncrowded beaches like Kudawa, Uchchimuni, and Kappalady offer pristine coastal relaxation. A perfect blend of adventure, marine life, and untouched natural beauty.',1,'Puttalam District, North Western Province, Sri Lanka',8.23560000,79.76610000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(87,'Kitulgala','Sri Lanka\'s premier adventure destination, nestled in a valley on the Kelani River surrounded by lush rainforest. Famous as the filming location for the Academy Award-winning movie \"The Bridge on the River Kwai.\" The star attraction is white water rafting on the Kelani River with rapids ranging from Class I to IV, suitable for both beginners and experienced rafters. Adventure seekers can also enjoy waterfall abseiling, rock climbing, confidence jumps into natural pools, and kayaking. The surrounding rainforest offers excellent hiking trails to waterfalls like Lakshapana (126m) and Sandun Ella, and is a paradise for bird watching with endemic species including the Green-billed Coucal and Red-faced Malkoha. The area preserves the ancient UNESCO-recognized practice of Kithul tapping, where local tappers extract sap to produce treacle, jaggery, and toddy.',1,'Sabaragamuwa Province, Sri Lanka (approx. 90km east of Colombo)',6.99000000,80.41000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(88,'Knuckles','A UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of Sri Lanka\'s most breathtaking mountain ranges, named for its resemblance to a clenched fist. The range features peaks exceeding 1,900 meters, covered in misty cloud forests, grasslands, and cascading waterfalls. A paradise for trekkers and nature lovers with trails through remote valleys, past 40 traditional villages, and to dramatic viewpoints like Mini World\'s End. Adventure activities include waterfall abseiling on 30-50 meter cascades, paragliding over the mountains, and air gun firing with stunning backdrops. The Heeloya Village experience offers immersion into 2,000-year-old agrarian traditions, including visits to ancient village council sites (Wariga Sabhawa) and traditional threshing floors (Kamatha). Overnight camping at riverside sites provides unforgettable experiences under starry skies.',1,'Central Province, Sri Lanka (near Matale)',7.50000000,80.80000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(89,'Mahiyanganaya','A town of immense historical and cultural significance in Sri Lanka\'s Uva Province. Home to the Dambana Vedda Village, where visitors can meet the indigenous Vedda people—direct descendants of the island\'s first inhabitants who have lived here for over 16,000 years. Experience authentic cultural encounters including guided village tours, traditional hunting demonstrations, fire-making techniques, medicinal plant knowledge, and vibrant dance performances. The Mahiyangana Raja Maha Viharaya marks the site of Buddha\'s first visit to Sri Lanka and houses the first stupa ever built on the island. Serene boat rides on Mapakada Lake offer stunning views of surrounding hills and opportunities to spot wildlife. A unique destination combining indigenous heritage, sacred Buddhism, and natural beauty.',1,'Uva Province, Sri Lanka (approx. 60km from Badulla)',7.31670000,81.00000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(90,'Mannar','A historic island town on Sri Lanka\'s northwest coast, deeply connected to the Ramayana epic and centuries of colonial history. Witness the legendary Ram Sethu (Adam\'s Bridge)—a chain of limestone shoals stretching 48km toward India, believed to be the bridge built by Lord Rama\'s army. Explore the 17th-century Mannar Dutch Fort with its moat, chapel ruins, and panoramic Gulf views. Visit the famous 700-year-old Baobab Tree in Pallimunai, brought by Arab merchants and the largest of its kind in Sri Lanka. The Thiruketheeswaram Temple, one of the five ancient Iswarams, is where the planetary being Ketu worshipped Shiva. The Shrine of Our Lady of Madhu is the holiest Catholic shrine in Sri Lanka, drawing pilgrims of all faiths. The Vankalai Bird Sanctuary (Ramsar wetland) hosts over 150 bird species including flamingos during migratory season.',1,'Mannar District, Northern Province, Sri Lanka',8.98330000,79.91670000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(91,'Matale','The cultural heart of Sri Lanka\'s hill country, famous for its aromatic spice gardens and proximity to UNESCO World Heritage sites. Visit government-recognized spice gardens where cinnamon, cardamom, pepper, and nutmeg grow in their natural environment, with guided tours explaining traditional harvesting techniques and Ayurvedic properties. The Aluvihara Rock Temple holds monumental significance as the place where the Pāli Canon (Buddhist scriptures) was first written down on palm leaves in the 1st Century BC. Strategically located as a gateway to the Knuckles Mountain Range (UNESCO) and en route to both Sigiriya and Dambulla Cave Temple. The nearby Riverston Gap offers spectacular 1,405m viewpoints, Mini World\'s End, and waterfalls like Sera Ella. A perfect base for exploring the Cultural Triangle and mountain wilderness.',1,'Central Province, Sri Lanka (26km north of Kandy)',7.46670000,80.61670000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(92,'Negombo','A vibrant coastal city just 10km from Bandaranaike International Airport, serving as the perfect introduction to Sri Lanka. Famous for its Saturday Night Market—a lively local experience with clothing, crafts, and street food open only on Saturdays 11AM-9PM. The Lellama Fish Market is Sri Lanka\'s second largest, operating from 2AM-8AM daily (closed Sundays) with 4,000 boats bringing in fresh seafood. St. Mary\'s Church, one of the country\'s largest Catholic churches, features stunning ceiling paintings by a Buddhist artist. The Dutch colonial legacy remains in the Hamilton Canal (17th century) offering peaceful boat rides through mangroves, and the Dutch Clock Tower. Boat tours through the lagoon reveal \"Monkey Island,\" mangrove forests, and spectacular sunsets. Traditional toddy tappers demonstrate the ancient art of extracting coconut sap, while water sports and coastal cycling opportunities abound.',1,'Western Province, Sri Lanka (10km north of Colombo airport)',7.21670000,79.83330000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(93,'Pasikudah','A pristine coastal paradise on Sri Lanka\'s east coast, renowned for its exceptionally calm, shallow turquoise waters—one of the world\'s longest shallow coastlines allowing visitors to walk far into the sea without encountering deep water. The crescent-shaped bay of Pasikudah offers safe swimming and water sports including jet skiing, windsurfing, kayaking, and snorkeling above vibrant coral reefs. Nearby Nilaveli Beach is famous for its pure white sand and access to Pigeon Island Marine National Park. Cultural excursions include the Kokkadicholai Thaanthonreeswarar Temple, one of Sri Lanka\'s earliest Hindu temples featuring a naturally formed Sivalingam and an 18th-century wooden chariot. Batticaloa\'s colonial lighthouse (1913) and lagoon boat trips to hear the famous \"singing fish\" complete the experience. Perfect for families, honeymooners, and those seeking serene coastal beauty.',1,'Eastern Province, Sri Lanka (approx. 30km from Batticaloa)',7.91670000,81.53330000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(94,'Sinharaja','Sri Lanka\'s last remaining primary tropical rainforest and a UNESCO World Heritage Site & Biosphere Reserve, spanning 11,200 hectares with elevations from 200-1,300 meters. This biodiversity hotspot is home to 95% of the country\'s endemic bird species, including 20 rainforest endemics such as the elusive Red-faced Malkoha, Green-billed Coucal (rarest), and stunning Sri Lanka Blue Magpie. Bird watchers flock to witness the fascinating phenomenon of \"mixed feeding flocks\"—20-30 species moving together through the forest. Trekking trails ranging from 3-7 hours lead through dense jungle past multiple waterfalls where visitors can swim in cool natural pools. Purple-faced Langurs are the most commonly seen mammals, while leopards and elephants exist but are rarely spotted. Guides are mandatory, ensuring safe navigation and expert wildlife spotting. A paradise for nature lovers, photographers, and serious birders.',1,'Sabaragamuwa and Southern Provinces, Sri Lanka',6.40690000,80.49940000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(95,'Trincomalee','A magnificent natural harbor city on Sri Lanka\'s northeast coast, blessed with stunning beaches, ancient temples, and world-class marine life. The Koneswaram Temple (Thousand Pillars Temple) perches dramatically on Swami Rock, dating back over 2,500 years with breathtaking ocean views from Lovers\' Leap. Fort Frederick, built by the Portuguese in 1623 and later fortified by the Dutch, still houses wild spotted deer roaming freely. The region\'s beaches—Uppuveli and Nilaveli—offer pristine white sands and access to Pigeon Island Marine National Park, where snorkelers and divers explore vibrant coral reefs alongside blacktip reef sharks and sea turtles. From March to May, the waters host Blue Whales and Sperm Whales, while spinner dolphins perform acrobatic displays from May to September. The Kanniya Hot Water Wells and Sri Badrakali Amman Temple add cultural depth to this coastal paradise.',1,'Eastern Province, Sri Lanka',8.58330000,81.25000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(96,'Udawalawe','A premier wildlife destination centered around the Udawalawe National Park, established in 1972 to provide sanctuary for animals displaced by reservoir construction. Spanning 30,821 hectares, the park is famed for its large population of approximately 250 Sri Lankan elephants, easily visible in open grasslands and around water sources. Safaris in 4x4 jeeps offer excellent opportunities to spot water buffalo, spotted deer, crocodiles, and if lucky, the elusive leopard. The park is also home to 30 snake varieties and 50 butterfly species, making it a biodiversity hotspot. The Elephant Transit Home (Ath Athuru Sewana) provides heartwarming conservation in action—visitors watch orphaned baby elephants being bottle-fed at scheduled times (10:30 AM, 2:30 PM, 6:00 PM) before their eventual release to the wild. Riverside camping experiences offer immersive nature stays with comfortable glamping tents and stunning river views.',1,'Sabaragamuwa and Uva Provinces, Sri Lanka',6.43810000,80.88890000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(97,'Udaweriya','A serene highland valley in Sri Lanka\'s tea country, serving as the endpoint for Stage 11 of the renowned Pekoe Trail. The spectacular 13-14km point-to-point hike from Horton Plains begins at the historic Farr Inn (2,170m) and descends via the famous \"Devil\'s Staircase\"—a steep, zigzagging dirt track named by Scottish planters offering breathtaking panoramic views. On exceptionally clear days, hikers can see Udawalawe National Park and even the distant southern coastline. The trail winds through a \"hidden valley\" at 1,618m on the edge of tea-growing country, passing vegetable terraces, local villages, the skeletal remains of the abandoned Udaweriya Tea Factory, and a small Christian church before concluding near the historic Ohiya Tea Factory. This 4-5 hour moderately challenging trek offers an immersive experience into Sri Lanka\'s diverse highland landscapes and cultural heritage.',1,'Central Highlands, Sri Lanka (near Ohiya)',6.80200000,80.80740000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(98,'Unawatuna','A picturesque crescent-shaped bay on Sri Lanka\'s south coast, renowned for its golden sands, crystal-clear turquoise waters, and relaxed bohemian atmosphere. Just 5km from Galle, it offers the perfect blend of beach relaxation and cultural exploration. The beach is lined with charming cafes and restaurants serving fresh seafood, with water sports including snorkeling above vibrant coral reefs, scuba diving at nearby shipwrecks, and surfing lessons (best November-April). Rumassala Hill, steeped in Ramayana legend as a piece of the Himalayan mountain dropped by Hanuman, features a Buddhist temple, the serene Japanese Peace Pagoda, and walking trails to secluded Jungle Beach. Nearby Koggala offers the iconic stilt fishermen experience, best photographed at sunrise or sunset. Unawatuna serves as an ideal base for exploring the UNESCO-listed Galle Dutch Fort, with its 14 bastions, lighthouse, and colonial charm.',1,'Southern Province, Sri Lanka (5km southeast of Galle)',6.01670000,80.25000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL),(99,'Wilpattu','Sri Lanka\'s largest and one of its oldest national parks, spanning an impressive 1,317 square kilometers and declared a national park in 1938. World-renowned for its significant leopard population, with approximately 40 individuals offering a 50% sighting success rate with experienced guides. The park\'s unique feature is its 106 natural \"Willus\"—rainwater lakes that attract diverse wildlife, making it the best place in Sri Lanka to spot the elusive sloth bear (30% success rate). Other wildlife includes Sri Lankan elephants, spotted deer, water buffalo, sambar, crocodiles, and over 200 bird species including migratory visitors from November to April. Closed for 16 years during the civil war (1983-2003), the park\'s pristine wilderness offers a more authentic, less crowded safari experience than Yala. Safaris in 4WD open-top jeeps explore dense dry-zone forests, scrublands, and open plains, with morning (6:00 AM) and afternoon (2:00 PM) departures available.',1,'North Western Province, Sri Lanka (30km from Anuradhapura)',8.43330000,80.00000000,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',1,'2026-02-20 09:09:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,0,NULL);
